==Trivia==
*In the comics, Wilson Fisk is a former member of [[Don Rigoletto]]'s crime family. Following murdering his boss, Fisk built his criminal empire within [[New York City]] and had encounters with [[Daredevil]], [[Spider-Man]] and the [[Punisher]].
*Fisk is partial to Italian food, such as Zuppa Inglese.{{Ref|DD104}} He also enjoys Chinese tea{{Ref|DD108}} and his wine of choice is Lafite.{{Ref|EC104}}
*Fisk is a fan of [[The Rolling Stones]].{{Ref|DD108}}
*Fisk is left-handed.
*Kingpin's outfit in the ''[[Hawkeye (TV series)|Hawkeye]]'' episode ''[[So This Is Christmas?]]'' was inspired by the ''Amazing Spider-Man: Family Business'' run, which was pitched by [[Vincent D'Onofrio]] himself.<ref>[https://www.murphysmultiverse.com/hawkeyes-vincent-donofrio-pitched-his-family-business-inspired-outfit/ ‘Hawkeye’s Vincent D’Onofrio Pitched His ‘Family Business’ Inspired Outfit]</ref>
*Kingpin is the first [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] character introduced in ''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]'' to subsequently appear in a [[Marvel Studios]] production.
*Kingpin has the distinction of being the only character in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] to be the main antagonist in both a [[Marvel Studios]] and a [[Marvel Television]] project.

==Behind the Scenes==
*Kingpin in the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]] is the third live-action incarnation of the character, following incarnations portrayed by {{WPS|John Rhys-Davies}} and {{WPS|Michael Clarke Duncan}}.
*The rights for Kingpin are shared between [[Marvel Studios]] and [[Sony Pictures Entertainment]]; Marvel is able to use him in live-action shows while Sony is allowed to use him in live-action movies and animated projects, such as the 2018 {{WPS|Sony Pictures Animation}} film ''{{WPS|Spider-Man: Into the Spider-Verse}}''. This may be due to the fact that Kingpin originally appeared as an enemy of [[Spider-Man]] (whose rights are owned by Sony), yet he is usually depicted as the arch-enemy of [[Daredevil]] (whose rights are owned by Marvel Studios).
*[[Vincent D'Onofrio]] commented that the main difference between Fisk's portrayal in ''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]'' and ''[[Hawkeye (TV series)|Hawkeye]]'' was his "physical strength." He also described him as "bigger [...] more like [he was in] the comics." Regardless of this, D'Onofrio said [[Marvel Studios]] was trying their best to keep the events of ''Daredevil'' canonical to the [[Marvel Cinematic Universe]]<ref name="GR+">[https://www.gamesradar.com/kingpin-vincent-donofrio-interview-hawkeye/ Kingpin actor Vincent D'Onofrio answers (and avoids) our burning Hawkeye questions | GamesRadar+]</ref> and that the writers, directors and producers of ''[[Hawkeye (TV series)|Hawkeye]]'' saw Kingpin's role as a continuation of his character from the Netflix series.<ref>[https://www.thewrap.com/hawkeye-vincent-donofrio-kingpin-dead/ ‘Hawkeye': Vincent D’Onofrio Hopes Kingpin’s Fate Is Not What It Looked Like (thewrap.com)]</ref><ref>[https://collider.com/hawkeye-is-kingpin-dead-vincent-donofrio-interview/ Hawkeye: Vincent D'Onofrio on Returning as Kingpin and His Character's Fate (collider.com)]</ref>
*''Hawkeye'' Costume Designer [[Michael Crow]] revealed that it was intended to move Kingpin away from his "polished look" in ''[[Daredevil (TV series)|Daredevil]]'' as [[Vincent D'Onofrio]] wanted him to look "a little more down and out and grittier than he had previously been [in Daredevil],"<ref>[https://www.insider.com/hawkeye-costume-designer-vincent-donofrio-kingpin-secret-day-of-filming-2021-12 'Hawkeye' Costume Designer Says He Only Met Vincent D'Onofrio the Day of Filming (insider.com)]</ref> as "[Kingpin] has lost the power that he had [once] in ''Daredevil''."<ref>[https://www.cinemablend.com/interviews/hawkeyes-vincent-donofrio-explains-mcu-kingpins-daredevil-connections Hawkeye’s Vincent D’Onofrio Explains MCU Kingpin’s Daredevil Connections | Cinemablend]</ref>
*[[Pete Klein]], [[Airon Armstrong]], [[Matt Leonard]], [[Chad Knorr]], [[Aden Stay]], [[Jean-Claude Leuyer]], [[Dan B. Norris]] and [[Josh Diogo]] were stunt doubles for [[Vincent D'Onofrio]] and [[James Northrup]] was a stunt double for [[Cole Jensen]] in the role of Kingpin.
*[[Kristoffe Brodeur]] was a stand-in for [[Vincent D'Onofrio]] in the role of Kingpin.

